T1  - Innovative Behavior in the Workplace: The Role of Performance and Image Outcome Expectations
AU  - Yuan, Feirong
AU  - Woodman, Richard W.
Y1  - 2010/04/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.49388995
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.49388995
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 323
EP  - 342
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Why do employees engage in innovative behavior at their workplaces? We examine how employees' innovative behavior is explained by expectations for such behavior to affect job performance (expected positive performance outcomes) and image inside their organizations (expected image risks and expected image gains). We found significant effects of all three outcome expectations on innovative behavior. These outcome expectations, as intermediate psychological processes, were shaped by contextual and individual difference factors, including perceived organization support for innovation, supervisor relationship quality, job requirement for innovativeness, employee reputation as innovative, and individual dissatisfaction with the status quo.
AB  - Why do employees engage in innovative behavior at their workplaces? We examine how employees' innovative behavior is explained by expectations for such behavior to affect job performance (expected positive performance outcomes) and image inside their organizations (expected image risks and expected image gains). We found significant effects of all three outcome expectations on innovative behavior. These outcome expectations, as intermediate psychological processes, were shaped by contextual and individual difference factors, including perceived organization support for innovation, supervisor relationship quality, job requirement for innovativeness, employee reputation as innovative, and individual dissatisfaction with the status quo.
